#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""pr-finalize — post a curated REVIEW.md to GitHub as one review object.

Companion to the `pr-review` script. pr-review prepares a PR and runs the
sandboxed review that writes REVIEW.md; a human curates it (checks the box on
each finding worth posting); pr-finalize posts the result. It takes no
arguments — the PR and the reviewed head come from the preparation snapshot
(.pr-review/state.json), never from REVIEW.md's frontmatter. REVIEW.md's *body*
is parsed for the curation state; the closed ### grammar makes that a machine's
job, so no model sits in the posting path.

Runs unsandboxed: it needs the network (a live head check and the POST) and
reads local files plus gh. The only external tool is gh — already required by
pr-review. JSON is built with the standard library, so there is no jq
dependency (gh embeds jq for its own output for the same reason standalone jq
can't be assumed present).

Routing is by SECTION ORDINAL, not heading text. A human may relabel a heading,
but the first three ## sections are Problems, Observations, Pre-existing, in
that order, and the empty-sections rule keeps the mapping stable:

  - sections 1 & 2: a located finding posts as an inline comment, and MUST land
    in the diff or the single review object would 422. An out-of-diff finding
    here is a misfiled pre-existing one or a stale anchor, and is refused — not
    silently rerouted. A locationless finding folds into the PR-level body
    under its (verbatim) heading label.
  - section 3: every finding folds, carrying a blob permalink when it is located.

Code links are authored one way throughout REVIEW.md — the VS Code-relative
](./path#line) grammar a ### heading already uses — so the same link is
navigable in the local checkout during curation whether it sits in a heading or
in prose. Prose and the body post to GitHub verbatim, where a relative link is
dead, so linkify_prose rewrites each to a blob permalink at post time (only the
posted copy; REVIEW.md on disk stays relative). In prose the #line fragment is
optional — a fragmentless ./path names the file and permalinks to it — because
only a ### heading's link is a comment anchor, and an anchor needs a line. A
fragment that is not a bare line number (./path#L52) is refused by name.

The review's verdict follows from curation alone: with no checked finding it is
posted as an APPROVE; with any checked finding — in any of the three sections,
since the checkbox (not the section) is the blocking signal — it is a
REQUEST_CHANGES. COMMENT is not used: GitHub drops a PR out of "review
requested" the moment any review lands, regardless of event, so a non-committal
COMMENT would only deny the author a next-step signal. An empty body is fine:
GitHub requires a REQUEST_CHANGES review to carry a body OR comments (verified
empirically; the docs' "body is required" wording overstates it), and every
REQUEST_CHANGES this tool sends carries one or the other by construction.

The review posts pinned to the reviewed commit, not the PR head: the create-review
POST sets commit_id to the reviewed head, so every inline anchor resolves against
the diff the review was written for. When the head has since moved, GitHub marks
the affected comments outdated — shown against the code as reviewed — rather than
relocating them onto whatever now sits at those line numbers. So a moved head is
reported, never refused: a curator who fixed a run of typos themselves, or
restructured something faster than it could be explained, keeps the curation. The
report is a WARNING banner naming all three heads — reviewed, local, PR — and what
moved; local commits the PR head does not carry are offered a push first,
fast-forward only, since a plain `git push` refuses anything else and so cannot
rewrite the contributor's branch. Permalinks are pinned to the reviewed head too,
and a blob is immutable.

The curator's own pending GitHub review (the "Start a review" flow) would 422
that POST — GitHub allows one pending review per user per PR. So when there is
one, pr-finalize does not post a separate object: it ADDS this review's findings
to the pending review and submits it. The curator's own comments are never
rebuilt or deleted, so whatever shape they take — replies, file-level, LEFT-side,
multi-line — rides along in the submit untouched (this retired the old refusal of
replies and file-level comments, which existed only because the create-review
payload could not express them). A finding is added at the reviewed head: as a
line-based thread when the pending review is itself anchored there (multi-line
capable), otherwise as a commit-pinned single-line comment via the deprecated
addPullRequestReviewComment (the only add that lets the commit be chosen). That
pin cannot carry a line range, so a checked RANGE finding on the pinned path is
refused by name — flattening it would corrupt a multi-line suggestion — with the
whole post held back so a re-run after the fix lands in one review. The submit
carries the verdict as its event and body_text as its body (which already folds
the pending draft in, since the submit body replaces the draft). A pending comment
is a human-authored finding, so its mere presence forces REQUEST_CHANGES.

Both post paths pin to the reviewed head, so a re-run after a lost response is
idempotent by two independent means: find_prior_post recognises an already-posted
review by our assembled body, and the augment path reconciles each finding against
the pending review's existing comments (by original commit, diff position and
body — a pending comment carries no line until it is submitted) before adding it,
so a partial add resumes rather than doubles. The pending review is
snapshotted to .pr-review-run/pending-import.json for the post-mortem.

The hard refusals are an already-posted preparation and a checked range finding
on the pinned-augment path (above).

On success REVIEW.md is kept — unchecked findings survive for a follow-up — and
a posted.md marker in the run directory closes the preparation, refusing a
second post here and a re-run from pr-review. Re-prepare to reopen.

Usage:  pr-finalize            post the prepared PR
        pr-finalize --dry-run  parse, route and print the payload; post nothing
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import json
import shutil
import sys
from pathlib import Path
from typing import TYPE_CHECKING, Any

if TYPE_CHECKING:
    import re

# The shared modules live beside this script: pr_review_lint (the REVIEW.md
# grammar, model and linter), pr_review_cleanup (the artifact wipe offered
# after posting, also used by pr-cleanup), and pr_review_common (logging, tty
# interaction, process helpers, artifact names). resolve() follows the
# ~/.local/bin symlink pr-install creates back to the real bin dir, where
# pr-install copies the modules alongside this file, so the imports work
# whether pr-finalize runs in place or through that symlink.
sys.path.insert(0, str(Path(__file__).resolve().parent))
from pr_review_cleanup import run_cleanup
from pr_review_common import (
    POSTED_NAME,
    REVIEW_NAME,
    RUN_DIR_NAME,
    STATE_DIR_NAME,
    NoTerminalError,
    confirm as _confirm,
    die,
    gh,
    gh_api_list,
    git,
    log,
    pause,
    run,
    set_prog,
)
from pr_review_lint import (
    PROSE_LINK,
    SECTION_COUNT,
    TEXT_END_L,
    Problem,
    Section,
    bail_on_problems,
    diff_position,
    lint,
    parse_diff_ranges,
    parse_review,
)

PROG = "pr-finalize"
set_prog(PROG)
STATE_DIR = Path(STATE_DIR_NAME)
RUN_DIR = Path(RUN_DIR_NAME)
REVIEW = Path(REVIEW_NAME)
POSTED_MD = RUN_DIR / POSTED_NAME
POSTED_JSON = RUN_DIR / "posted.json"
PENDING_IMPORT = RUN_DIR / "pending-import.json"


# --- routing and assembly -----------------------------------------------------

def permalink(nwo: str, head: str, path: str,
              start: int | None = None, end: int | None = None) -> str:
    """A blob permalink at the reviewed head, line-pinned when given a start.

    Without a start it names the file as a whole, which GitHub serves fine — the
    line fragment is only compulsory where a link becomes a comment ANCHOR."""
    url = f"https://github.com/{nwo}/blob/{head}/{path}"
    if start is None:
        return url
    frag = f"L{start}" + (f"-L{end}" if end and end > start else "")
    return f"{url}#{frag}"


def linkify_prose(text: str, nwo: str, head: str) -> str:
    """Rewrite every VS Code-relative code link in prose to a blob permalink.

    Code links are authored one way everywhere — ](./path#start), the same
    grammar a ### heading carries — navigable in the local checkout; but prose
    and the body post to GitHub verbatim, where a relative link resolves to
    nothing, so each is converted here at post time (only the posted copy;
    REVIEW.md on disk keeps its relative links). The #start fragment is the start
    line; a trailing -L<end> in the link TEXT extends it to a range, otherwise
    the permalink is single-line. A fragmentless target names the whole file and
    yields a fragmentless permalink. Absolute links (a curator-pasted permalink)
    start with a scheme, not ./, so they pass through untouched.

    Assumes a lint-clean tree: pr_review_lint.check_fragments has already refused
    any fragment that is not a bare line, so every #frag reached here is digits."""
    def repl(m: re.Match[str]) -> str:
        link_text, target = m.group(1), m.group(2)
        if "#" in target:
            path, _, frag = target.rpartition("#")
            start: int | None = int(frag)
            em = TEXT_END_L.search(link_text)
            end = int(em.group(1)) if em else start
        else:
            path, start, end = target, None, None
        return f"[{link_text}]({permalink(nwo, head, path, start, end)})"
    return PROSE_LINK.sub(repl, text)


def route(sections: list[Section], nwo: str, head: str
          ) -> tuple[list[dict[str, Any]], list[tuple[str, str, list[str]]]]:
    """Sort checked findings into inline comments and body-folded groups.

    Assumes a lint-clean tree (pr_review_lint.lint has passed): every inline
    anchor is in the diff, no checked finding sits past the third section, and
    every contributing section is labeled — so this only builds, never judges.
    Returns (comments, fold_groups) where a fold group is
    (label, preamble, [rendered finding text...]) in file order.
    """
    comments: list[dict[str, Any]] = []
    fold_groups: list[tuple[str, str, list[str]]] = []

    for s in sections:
        if s.ordinal > SECTION_COUNT:  # lint-guaranteed to carry no checked finding
            continue
        items: list[str] = []
        for b in s.blocks:
            if not b.checked:
                continue
            prose = linkify_prose(b.prose, nwo, head)

            # Sections 1 & 2, located: inline. lint has confirmed both endpoints
            # are in the diff, so neither the create-review POST nor the pinned add
            # can fail to place it. review_line is internal — the finding's ### line
            # in REVIEW.md, carried so a refusal can point the curator back at it,
            # and stripped before the payload (it is not an API field).
            loc = b.location()
            if loc is not None and s.ordinal in (1, 2):
                path, start, end = loc
                comment: dict[str, Any] = {"path": path, "body": prose, "line": end,
                                           "side": "RIGHT", "review_line": b.head_line}
                if end > start:
                    comment["start_line"] = start
                    comment["start_side"] = "RIGHT"
                comments.append(comment)
                continue

            # Everything else folds: section 3 (any), sections 1 & 2 locationless.
            if loc is not None:
                path, start, end = loc
                base = path.rsplit("/", 1)[-1]
                rng = f"L{start}" + (f"-L{end}" if end > start else "")
                link = permalink(nwo, head, path, start, end)
                items.append(f"[{base} {rng}]({link})\n\n{prose}")
            else:
                items.append(prose)

        if items:
            # The preamble folds into the body ahead of the group, so its links
            # convert too (only when the section actually contributes).
            fold_groups.append((s.label, linkify_prose(s.preamble, nwo, head), items))

    return comments, fold_groups


def assemble_body(body: str, fold_groups: list[tuple[str, str, list[str]]]) -> str:
    """The PR-level comment: the curated body (status table and any coverage
    caveat), then each contributing section under its label, with its preamble
    copied verbatim, then its findings."""
    parts: list[str] = []
    if body:
        parts.append(body)
    if fold_groups:
        parts.append("---")
        for label, preamble, items in fold_groups:
            parts.append(f"**{label}**")
            if preamble:
                parts.append(preamble)
            parts.extend(items)
    return ("\n\n".join(parts)).strip() + "\n"


def format_recap(sections: list[Section], comments: list[dict[str, Any]], fold_count: int,
                 event: str, pending_comments: list[dict[str, Any]], has_draft: bool,
                 *, moved: bool) -> str:
    """Human-readable curation recap printed before the prompt: per-section
    checked/unchecked/total, the curator's pending review when there is one, a
    reminder when the PR head has moved, then the verdict about to be posted. A
    section that shows 0 checked is the cue for a REVIEW.md that was never read
    to the end."""
    lines = [f"{PROG}: REVIEW.md recap"]
    width = max((len(s.label) for s in sections), default=0)
    for s in sections:
        total = len(s.blocks)
        checked = sum(1 for b in s.blocks if b.checked)
        lines.append(f"  §{s.ordinal} {s.label:<{width}}  checked {checked}"
                     f" / unchecked {total - checked} / total {total}")
    if pending_comments:
        paths = ", ".join(sorted({c.get("path", "?") for c in pending_comments}))
        lines.append(f"  + pending review: {len(pending_comments)} comment(s) of yours, "
                     f"submitted with the review — {paths}")
    if has_draft:
        lines.append("  + pending review: your draft body appended to the review body")
    if moved:
        lines.append(f"  ! PR head moved since the review — {len(comments)} inline "
                     "comment(s) post at the reviewed commit (outdated where newer "
                     "commits touched those lines)")
    if event == "APPROVE":
        lines.append("  → verdict: APPROVE (no findings checked)")
    else:
        detail = f"{len(comments)} inline, {fold_count} folded"
        if pending_comments:
            detail += f", {len(pending_comments)} pending"
        lines.append("  → verdict: REQUEST_CHANGES "
                     f"({len(comments) + fold_count + len(pending_comments)} finding(s): "
                     f"{detail})")
    return "\n".join(lines) + "\n"


# --- the curator's pending review -----------------------------------------------

def fetch_pending_review(nwo: str, pr_id: str) -> tuple[dict[str, Any] | None, list[dict[str, Any]]]:
    """The curator's own pending review on the PR, with its comments, verbatim.

    GitHub shows a pending review only to its author and allows one per user
    per PR, so at most one is visible here — and while it exists, a create-review
    POST is rejected with 422 even with an event supplied, which is why this run
    augments and submits that review rather than posting a separate one."""
    reviews = gh_api_list(f"repos/{nwo}/pulls/{pr_id}/reviews",
                          what=f"listing PR #{pr_id} reviews")
    pending = [r for r in reviews if r.get("state") == "PENDING"]
    if not pending:
        return None, []
    if len(pending) > 1:
        die(f"PR #{pr_id} shows {len(pending)} pending reviews; GitHub allows one "
            "per user and shows only your own, so this should be impossible. "
            "Resolve them on github.com, then re-run.")
    review = pending[0]
    comments = gh_api_list(f"repos/{nwo}/pulls/{pr_id}/reviews/{review['id']}/comments",
                           what="fetching the pending review's comments")
    return review, comments


# --- the interactive confirmation ---------------------------------------------

def confirm(prompt: str) -> bool:
    """A y/N answer on the controlling terminal (the shared helper), with
    pr-finalize's own message when there is no terminal to answer from — a POST is
    irreversible, so it needs a real keystroke a pipe or heredoc cannot pre-answer."""
    try:
        return _confirm(prompt)
    except NoTerminalError:
        die("posting is irreversible and needs an interactive terminal to confirm. "
            "Run pr-finalize from a shell, or use --dry-run to preview.")


# --- the git position -----------------------------------------------------------

def have_commit(sha: str) -> bool:
    """True when sha names a commit object in this repository."""
    return run("git", "cat-file", "-e", f"{sha}^{{commit}}").returncode == 0


def is_ancestor(base: str, tip: str) -> bool:
    """True when base is an ancestor of tip. Both must be local objects."""
    return run("git", "merge-base", "--is-ancestor", base, tip).returncode == 0


def count_commits(base: str, tip: str) -> int:
    """How many commits tip carries that base does not; 0 when either is unknown."""
    if not (have_commit(base) and have_commit(tip)):
        return 0
    p = run("git", "rev-list", "--count", f"{base}..{tip}")
    return int(p.stdout.strip()) if p.returncode == 0 else 0


def relation(base: str, other: str) -> str:
    """Where other sits relative to base, as the short annotation the banner prints.

    A head this checkout does not have — usually one the author pushed — cannot
    be placed, and is named as moved rather than guessed at. Nothing here
    fetches: writing to the repository is preparation's job."""
    if other == base:
        return "unchanged"
    if not (have_commit(base) and have_commit(other)):
        return "moved (not in this checkout)"
    if is_ancestor(base, other):
        return f"{count_commits(base, other)} commit(s) ahead"
    if is_ancestor(other, base):
        return f"{count_commits(other, base)} commit(s) behind"
    return "diverged"


def format_position(reviewed: str, local: str, live: str) -> str:
    """The three heads as a banner block, printed when they no longer agree.

    Preparation left all three equal — it force-pushed the rebased branch and
    recorded the result — so a disagreement is news, and the banner says which
    way. It shouts because it lands in a wall of progress output on the way to a
    prompt, and a curator who skims past it posts anchors that have drifted."""
    lines = [f"{PROG}: *** WARNING: GIT POSITION MISMATCH ***",
             f"  reviewed head  {reviewed[:12]}  — what REVIEW.md's findings point at",
             f"  local HEAD     {local[:12]}  — {relation(reviewed, local)}",
             f"  PR head        {live[:12]}  — {relation(reviewed, live)}, on GitHub"]
    if live == reviewed:
        lines.append("  The PR head still matches the review; nothing has moved.")
    else:
        lines.append("  The review posts pinned to the reviewed commit, so its comments show")
        lines.append("  against the code as reviewed — GitHub marks them outdated where later")
        lines.append("  commits changed those lines, never onto different code. But the review")
        lines.append("  now describes code the PR has moved past: post it, or re-prepare fresh.")
    return "\n".join(lines) + "\n"


def offer_push(pr_id: str, local: str, live: str, *, dry_run: bool) -> str:
    """Offer to push the local commits the PR head does not carry; return the PR head.

    Fast-forward only, and structurally so: the caller has established that the
    PR head is an ancestor of the local HEAD, and a plain `git push` refuses
    anything else — rewriting the contributor's branch belongs to preparation,
    which takes a lease for it. Returns local once pushed and live otherwise;
    declining is not an error, it only leaves the curator's own fixes invisible
    to the author."""
    ahead = count_commits(live, local)
    remote = run("git", "config", f"branch.pr/{pr_id}.remote").stdout.strip()
    ref = run("git", "config", f"branch.pr/{pr_id}.merge").stdout.strip()
    if not remote or not ref:
        log(f"{ahead} local commit(s) are not on the PR head, but branch pr/{pr_id} has no "
            "push destination in its config — no push offered.")
        return live
    if dry_run:
        log(f"{ahead} local commit(s) are not on the PR head; a real run would offer to "
            f"push them to {remote} ({ref}).")
        return live
    if not confirm(f"{PROG}: push your {ahead} local commit(s) to {remote} ({ref}) "
                   "before posting? [y/N] "):
        log("not pushed. The author will not see those commits, and any finding you "
            "fixed in them still reads as unfixed.")
        return live
    # The explicit sha, not HEAD: this function reports and returns `local`, so
    # pushing anything else would let the two part company silently.
    p = run("git", "push", remote, f"{local}:{ref}")
    if p.returncode != 0:
        die(f"pushing to {remote} ({ref}) failed: {p.stderr.strip() or 'git error'}. "
            "Nothing posted. Only a fast-forward is attempted here, so a PR head rewritten "
            f"meanwhile stops it — re-prepare in that case: pr-review {pr_id}.")
    log(f"pushed — the PR head is now {local[:12]}.")
    return local


# --- the lost-response guard --------------------------------------------------

def whoami() -> str:
    """Our GitHub login, for telling our own reviews from anyone else's."""
    return gh("api", "user", "--jq", ".login", what="reading your GitHub login").strip()


def find_prior_post(nwo: str, pr_id: str, our_body: str, login: str) -> dict[str, Any] | None:
    """A review of ours already carrying our_body, or None — the lost-response guard.

    A create-review POST can succeed while its HTTP response is lost (a dropped
    connection reads as a failure), and a naive re-run would post a second copy.
    our_body — the body assembled from REVIEW.md, before any pending draft is
    appended — is a deterministic fingerprint, recomputed identically on a re-run,
    so a review of ours whose body CONTAINS it (substring: a draft may follow it)
    is that first post. Empty our_body is skipped: it would match anything, and an
    empty-bodied review carries no comments to double either, so the cost of
    missing it is at most a duplicate APPROVE, never a lost finding. Matched to our
    own login, so another user quoting the review cannot masquerade as our prior
    post and suppress a real one. A PENDING review is skipped: this endpoint returns
    our own pending review too (it is what fetch_pending_review reads), and a draft
    is by definition not a completed post — mistaking one for a prior post would
    write the marker, closing the preparation over a review nobody ever sent."""
    probe = our_body.strip()
    if not probe:
        return None
    reviews = gh_api_list(f"repos/{nwo}/pulls/{pr_id}/reviews",
                          what=f"listing PR #{pr_id} reviews")
    for r in reviews:
        if r.get("state") == "PENDING":
            continue
        if (r.get("user") or {}).get("login") == login and probe in (r.get("body") or ""):
            return r
    return None


def pending_untouched(pr_id: str) -> str:
    """The note the lost-response recovery owes a curator who also has a pending review.

    The recovery short-circuits ahead of the augment path — a completed prior post is
    the whole review, and nothing can be added to it — so the pending review is left
    exactly as it was. Saying nothing would read as "handled": the marker the recovery
    writes closes the preparation, so pr-finalize will never reach that pending review
    again. Tense-neutral and shared by the dry run and the real run, so the preview and
    the act cannot drift."""
    return (f"a pending review of yours is also open on PR #{pr_id}; the recovery does not "
            "touch it, and the marker closes this preparation, so pr-finalize cannot add to "
            f"it any more. Submit it on github.com, or re-prepare (pr-review {pr_id}) to fold "
            "it into a fresh review.")


def mark_posted(review_url: str, record: dict[str, Any]) -> int:
    """Write the posted markers — posted.md (the guard) first, then posted.json.

    Returns 0, or 1 when the guard itself could not be written (the review is live
    but unlocked, reported loudly). A failed posted.json is only a warning: the
    guard is what stops a double-post. Shared by the normal post and the
    lost-response recovery, so the two write the same marker the same way."""
    RUN_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True)
    try:
        shutil.copyfile(REVIEW, POSTED_MD)
    except OSError as e:
        log(f"POSTED OK ({review_url}) but could not write the marker "
            f"{POSTED_MD}: {e}. The review is live; do NOT re-run — create "
            f"{POSTED_MD} by hand to lock it.")
        return 1
    try:
        POSTED_JSON.write_text(json.dumps(record, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))
    except OSError as e:
        log(f"warning — posted.json not written ({e}), but the posted.md "
            f"marker is set (no double-post risk). Review: {review_url}")
    return 0


# --- augment and submit ------------------------------------------------------

# Adding a comment to an existing pending review needs GraphQL: the REST
# create-review-comment endpoint refuses while a pending review exists (it would
# open a second one). addPullRequestReviewThread is the modern, line-based add
# but anchors to the review's own commit; addPullRequestReviewComment is the
# deprecated, position-based add — the only one that lets the commit be chosen,
# so the only way to pin an added finding to the reviewed head when the review is
# anchored elsewhere. It carries no line range, hence the single-line limit on
# that path (guarded below).
_ADD_THREAD = (
    "mutation($rid:ID!,$path:String!,$body:String!,$line:Int!,$side:DiffSide!,"
    "$startLine:Int,$startSide:DiffSide){addPullRequestReviewThread(input:{"
    "pullRequestReviewId:$rid,path:$path,body:$body,line:$line,side:$side,"
    "startLine:$startLine,startSide:$startSide}){thread{id}}}")
_ADD_COMMENT = (
    "mutation($rid:ID!,$path:String!,$body:String!,$commitOID:GitObjectID!,$position:Int!){"
    "addPullRequestReviewComment(input:{pullRequestReviewId:$rid,path:$path,body:$body,"
    "commitOID:$commitOID,position:$position}){comment{databaseId}}}")


def graphql(query: str, variables: dict[str, Any], what: str,
            recovery: str = "") -> dict[str, Any]:
    """Run a GraphQL request via gh, returning its `data`. Dies with `what` on a
    transport error or a GraphQL `errors` array (a 200 with errors is a failure);
    `recovery`, if given, is appended to the failure message (e.g. how to resume)."""
    p = run("gh", "api", "graphql", "--input", "-",
            stdin=json.dumps({"query": query, "variables": variables}))
    if p.returncode != 0:
        die(f"{what} failed: {p.stderr.strip() or 'gh error'}.{recovery}")
    try:
        out = json.loads(p.stdout)
    except ValueError:
        die(f"{what} failed: unparseable response:\n{p.stdout}{recovery}")
    if out.get("errors"):
        die(f"{what} failed: {json.dumps(out['errors'])}.{recovery}")
    return out.get("data") or {}


def comment_key(commit: str | None, path: str | None, position: int | None,
                body: str) -> tuple[str | None, str | None, int | None, str]:
    """Reconciliation identity for a review comment.

    Its anchor — original commit and original diff POSITION — plus its body,
    whitespace-normalized (GitHub round-trips line endings). Position, not line:
    reconciliation runs against the still-PENDING review, whose comments carry a
    position but leave line null until the review is submitted. Both augment paths
    anchor a finding at the reviewed head, so its position is diff_position(the
    canonical diff, …) — recomputed identically on a re-run, so an already-added
    finding matches and is skipped rather than doubled. Body stays in the key so a
    locally rephrased finding no longer matches and re-posts (a visible duplicate)
    instead of being silently dropped."""
    norm = "\n".join(ln.rstrip() for ln in (body or "").replace("\r\n", "\n").split("\n")).strip()
    return (commit, path, position, norm)


def post_augment(nwo: str, pr_id: str, pending: dict[str, Any],
                 existing: list[dict[str, Any]], comments: list[dict[str, Any]],
                 body_text: str, event: str, head: str, diff_text: str) -> str:
    """Add our inline findings to the curator's pending review, then submit it.

    Returns the submitted review's html_url. The curator's own comments are never
    touched — they ride along in the submit at their own anchors. Our findings
    anchor at the reviewed head: a pending review already anchored there takes them
    as threads (line-based, multi-line capable); one anchored elsewhere takes them
    as commit-pinned single-line comments. Reconciled against the review's existing
    comments, so a re-run after a partial add resumes rather than doubling."""
    review_node = pending["node_id"]
    pinned = (pending.get("commit_id") or "") != head

    # Pre-flight, pinned path only: the commit-pinned add is single-line, so a
    # checked range finding cannot keep both its range and its pin. Refuse by name
    # rather than flatten — a flattened multi-line suggestion would corrupt — and
    # refuse the whole post, so a re-run after the fix lands in one review.
    if pinned:
        ranged = [c for c in comments if c.get("start_line") is not None]
        if ranged:
            listing = "\n".join(
                f"  - REVIEW.md:{c.get('review_line', '?')}  —  "
                f"{c['path']} L{c['start_line']}-L{c['line']}" for c in ranged)
            die("your pending review is anchored at a commit other than the reviewed "
                "head, so each finding added to it must be pinned to a single line — but "
                f"these checked finding(s) span a line range:\n{listing}\n"
                "Pin your comments on a single line, if possible; alternatively, submit or "
                f"discard your pending review on https://github.com/{nwo}/pull/{pr_id}. "
                "Then run pr-finalize again.\n"
                "Nothing was posted.")

    present = {comment_key(c.get("original_commit_id"), c.get("path"),
                           c.get("original_position"), c.get("body") or "") for c in existing}
    added = skipped = 0
    for c in comments:
        # Identify a finding by its clickable REVIEW.md line first (the VS Code
        # terminal linkifies it), then its code location — so any failure below
        # points the curator straight back at the block to fix.
        where = f"REVIEW.md:{c.get('review_line', '?')} ({c['path']}:{c['line']})"
        # Position both keys the finding (against the pending comments above) and,
        # on the pinned path, places the add. lint has already put every inline
        # finding in the diff, so it resolves — but a None only weakens the key to
        # "add anyway" on the thread path, and hard-fails the pin below.
        pos = diff_position(diff_text, c["path"], c["line"], c.get("side", "RIGHT"))
        if comment_key(head, c["path"], pos, c["body"]) in present:
            skipped += 1
            continue
        # A failed add leaves the earlier ones in the pending review; reconciliation
        # skips them next time, so a re-run resumes rather than doubles.
        resume = " Run pr-finalize again to resume."
        if pinned:
            if pos is None:
                die(f"could not place {where} in the reviewed diff, so it cannot be "
                    "pinned to the reviewed commit. Nothing more was added; your pending "
                    f"review is intact. Re-prepare if the diff is stale: pr-review {pr_id}.")
            graphql(_ADD_COMMENT, {"rid": review_node, "path": c["path"], "body": c["body"],
                                   "commitOID": head, "position": pos},
                    what=f"adding {where} to your pending review", recovery=resume)
        else:
            graphql(_ADD_THREAD, {"rid": review_node, "path": c["path"], "body": c["body"],
                                  "line": c["line"], "side": c.get("side", "RIGHT"),
                                  "startLine": c.get("start_line"),
                                  "startSide": c.get("start_side") if c.get("start_line") else None},
                    what=f"adding {where} to your pending review", recovery=resume)
        added += 1
    log(f"added {added} finding(s) to your pending review"
        + (f", skipped {skipped} already present" if skipped else "") + ".")

    # Submit. The event carries the verdict; the body replaces the pending draft,
    # so body_text must already fold the draft in (assembly did). Not the gh()
    # helper: a failure past the first add must point at the intact pending review.
    p = run("gh", "api", "--method", "POST",
            f"repos/{nwo}/pulls/{pr_id}/reviews/{pending['id']}/events",
            "--input", "-", stdin=json.dumps({"event": event, "body": body_text}))
    if p.returncode != 0:
        die(f"submitting your pending review failed: {p.stderr.strip() or 'gh error'}. "
            "The added findings remain in it — re-run to resume, or submit it on "
            f"https://github.com/{nwo}/pull/{pr_id}.")
    try:
        url = (json.loads(p.stdout) or {}).get("html_url", "")
    except ValueError:
        url = ""
    if not url:
        die("submitting your pending review returned no URL — treating it as a failure. "
            f"Re-run to resume. Response:\n{p.stdout}")
    return url


# --- main ---------------------------------------------------------------------

def main(argv: list[str]) -> int:
    """Run the pre-post checks and post the curated REVIEW.md (see module docstring)."""
    dry_run = False
    for arg in argv:
        if arg == "--dry-run":
            dry_run = True
        else:
            die(f"unexpected argument: {arg} (usage: pr-finalize [--dry-run])")

    if shutil.which("gh") is None:
        die("GitHub CLI (gh) is not installed. Install it "
            "(https://github.com/cli/cli#installation), then try again.")

    # Repo root: REVIEW.md and the snapshot live here.
    top = git("rev-parse", "--show-toplevel", what="locating the repository")
    if Path(top).resolve() != Path.cwd().resolve():
        die(f"run pr-finalize from the repository root: {top}")

    if not STATE_DIR.joinpath("state.json").is_file():
        die(f"no preparation snapshot ({STATE_DIR/'state.json'}). "
            "Prepare and review first: pr-review <id>.")
    try:
        state = json.loads(STATE_DIR.joinpath("state.json").read_text())
    except (OSError, ValueError) as e:
        die(f"could not read the preparation snapshot: {e}")
    pr_id = str(state.get("prId", "")).strip()
    head = str(state.get("head", "")).strip()
    if not pr_id.isdigit():
        die("state.json has no usable prId — the snapshot is broken. Re-prepare.")
    if not head:
        die("state.json has no head — the snapshot is broken. Re-prepare.")

    branch = git("rev-parse", "--abbrev-ref", "HEAD", what="reading the branch")
    if branch != f"pr/{pr_id}":
        die(f"not on the prepared branch (HEAD is '{branch}', expected 'pr/{pr_id}'). "
            f"Check it out, or re-prepare: pr-review {pr_id}.")

    if not REVIEW.is_file():
        die("no REVIEW.md at the repo root — nothing curated to post. "
            f"Run the review first: pr-review {pr_id}.")

    # Terminal-state guard: a posted marker closes this preparation.
    if POSTED_MD.exists():
        die(f"PR #{pr_id} was already finalized ({POSTED_MD}). REVIEW.md is kept for "
            f"follow-up; to post again, re-prepare (pr-review {pr_id}) — a fresh "
            "preparation of the current head.")

    # gh signed in (clearer than letting the first API call fail).
    if run("gh", "auth", "status").returncode != 0:
        die("gh is installed but not signed in. Run 'gh auth login', then try again.")

    # Resolve the repo and print the PR's URL first thing — so it can be opened in
    # a browser (ctrl-click) while the slower live-head check, parsing and routing
    # below run. This needs only the repo name, already in hand from the snapshot's
    # pr_id plus gh's default repo.
    nwo = gh("repo", "view", "--json", "nameWithOwner", "--jq", ".nameWithOwner",
             what="resolving the repository").strip()
    if not nwo:
        die("gh returned no repository name; is a default repo set?")
    log(f"PR #{pr_id} — https://github.com/{nwo}/pull/{pr_id}")

    # The git position. Preparation left the reviewed head, the local HEAD and the
    # PR head equal; the author pushing, or the curator fixing something mid-review,
    # parts them. Neither is a reason to discard a finished curation, so a mismatch
    # is reported here and confirmed below — never refused.
    local_head = git("rev-parse", "HEAD", what="reading the local HEAD")
    live_head = gh("pr", "view", pr_id, "--json", "headRefOid", "--jq", ".headRefOid",
                   what=f"reading PR #{pr_id} head").strip()
    if live_head != head or local_head != head:
        sys.stderr.write(format_position(head, local_head, live_head))
        # Unpushed local commits: the author cannot see them, and any finding they
        # already fix still reads as unfixed. Offered only as a fast-forward.
        if (local_head != live_head and have_commit(live_head)
                and is_ancestor(live_head, local_head)):
            live_head = offer_push(pr_id, local_head, live_head, dry_run=dry_run)
    # Only the PR head decides where an inline comment lands; a local HEAD that ran
    # ahead is worth reporting, but costs the post nothing.
    moved = live_head != head

    # The curator's own pending review (GitHub's "Start a review" flow) blocks a
    # create-review POST — one pending review per user per PR — so when there is
    # one, this run adds its findings to that review and submits it, rather than
    # posting a separate object. Fetch it (fresh every run: comments the curator
    # edited on github.com between runs are picked up) and persist a snapshot for
    # the post-mortem. The curator's comments are never rebuilt or deleted, so any
    # shape they take — replies, file-level — rides along in the submit untouched.
    pending, pending_comments = fetch_pending_review(nwo, pr_id)
    draft_body = ""
    if pending is not None:
        draft_body = (pending.get("body") or "").strip()
        RUN_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True)
        try:
            PENDING_IMPORT.write_text(json.dumps(
                {"review": pending, "comments": pending_comments},
                ensure_ascii=False, indent=2))
        except OSError as e:
            die(f"could not persist the pending review to {PENDING_IMPORT}: {e}. "
                "Nothing was posted.")

    ranges_path = STATE_DIR / "canonical.diff"
    diff_text = ranges_path.read_text() if ranges_path.is_file() else ""
    ranges = parse_diff_ranges(diff_text)

    # Parse, then lint the whole file into one batch and report it in file order
    # before building or posting anything: parse_review and the lint pass in
    # pr_review_lint collect every fault, so a curator sees every misfiled
    # finding, unlabeled section and malformed link at once rather than one
    # re-run per fault. It lints against the preparation's canonical diff — the
    # surface the review was written for — so a head that moved since does not
    # change what it reports; routing below may then assume a valid tree.
    problems: list[Problem] = []
    body, body_line, sections = parse_review(REVIEW.read_text(), problems)
    lint(body, body_line, sections, ranges, problems)
    bail_on_problems(problems, PROG, "nothing posted")

    body = linkify_prose(body, nwo, head)  # lint-clean now: the body always posts
    comments, fold_groups = route(sections, nwo, head)

    our_body = assemble_body(body, fold_groups)  # what we assembled, before any draft
    body_text = our_body
    fold_count = sum(len(items) for _, _, items in fold_groups)

    # The pending review's draft body (summary text typed but not submitted)
    # rides along at the end of the assembled body, separated by ---.
    if draft_body:
        stripped = body_text.strip()
        body_text = (f"{stripped}\n\n---\n\n{draft_body}\n" if stripped
                     else f"{draft_body}\n")

    # Verdict by curation: any checked finding (in any section) blocks; none
    # approves. The checkbox is the blocking signal, not the section — and a
    # comment in the curator's pending review is a human-authored finding, checked
    # by the act of writing it, so it blocks too.
    event = "REQUEST_CHANGES" if (comments or fold_count or pending_comments) else "APPROVE"

    # An empty body is fine. GitHub requires a REQUEST_CHANGES review to carry
    # a body OR comments (verified empirically; the docs' "body is required"
    # wording overstates it), and REQUEST_CHANGES here implies comments,
    # fold_count, or a pending comment — and any folded finding makes the body
    # non-empty — so every request this sends is legal by construction.
    #
    # commit_id pins the review to the reviewed head. Without it GitHub defaults
    # to the PR's latest commit and resolves every anchor against the diff as it
    # is now — so once the head moved, a comment computed against the reviewed
    # diff would land on whatever now sits at that line number. Pinned, GitHub
    # instead marks a comment outdated where a later commit changed its line,
    # showing it against the code as reviewed: outdated, never misplaced. When
    # the head has not moved this is the latest commit anyway, so it is a no-op.
    # (The pinned-augment path pins per comment instead; see post_augment.)
    # review_line is internal bookkeeping (a REVIEW.md line, see route); strip it —
    # it is not a create-review comment field. post_augment reads it off `comments`
    # directly, so only this payload copy needs the projection.
    api_comments = [{k: v for k, v in c.items() if k != "review_line"} for c in comments]
    payload = {"body": body_text, "event": event, "commit_id": head, "comments": api_comments}
    recap = format_recap(sections, comments, fold_count, event, pending_comments,
                         bool(draft_body), moved=moved)

    # The lost-response guard: a prior run may have posted this review and lost the
    # response before writing the marker (a dropped connection reads as a failure).
    # A review of ours already carrying this body is that post — recover rather than
    # post a second copy. Read-only, so it runs in a dry run too (as a note).
    prior = find_prior_post(nwo, pr_id, our_body, whoami())

    if dry_run:
        print(json.dumps(payload, indent=2, ensure_ascii=False))
        sys.stderr.write(recap)
        # Order matters, and so does the elif: the recovery short-circuits ahead of
        # the augment path, so when both apply the augment is precisely what would
        # NOT happen. Announcing it first would preview a post the real run never makes.
        if prior is not None:
            log(f"note: a review of yours already carries this body "
                f"({prior.get('html_url', '')}); a real run would treat this as an "
                "already-completed post and write the marker instead of re-posting.")
            if pending is not None:
                log(pending_untouched(pr_id))
        elif pending is not None:
            how = ("as threads at the reviewed head"
                   if (pending.get("commit_id") or "") == head
                   else "pinned single-line (your review is anchored at another commit)")
            log(f"a pending review of yours exists on PR #{pr_id}; finalizing will add "
                f"these findings to it ({how}) and submit it, its own comments kept "
                f"(snapshot: {PENDING_IMPORT}).")
        log("dry run — nothing posted.")
        return 0

    sys.stderr.write(recap)

    if prior is not None:
        url = prior.get("html_url", "")
        log(f"a review of yours already carries this body — a prior post whose "
            f"response was lost: {url}. Nothing re-posted; writing the marker.")
        if pending is not None:
            log(pending_untouched(pr_id))
        return mark_posted(url, {"recovered": True, "review_url": url,
                                 "review_id": prior.get("id"),
                                 "heads": {"reviewed": head, "local": local_head,
                                           "pr": live_head}})

    # No separate moved-head gate. Pinning makes a moved head safe by construction
    # (outdated, never misplaced), so the WARNING banner up top and the recap's
    # moved line are notice, not a risk to clear — the confirmation below is the one
    # decision, and it fires whether or not the head moved.

    # One confirmation, worded for the path: with a pending review the act is a
    # submit (its comments plus our findings, as one review); without, a post.
    submit = pending is not None
    if event == "APPROVE":
        # No findings checked. That can mean "read it, it's clean" — or "never
        # finished reading it". Two gates, the second naming that risk, before an
        # approval that cannot be taken back.
        verb = ("submit your pending review as an APPROVE" if submit
                else "post an APPROVE review")
        if not confirm(f"{PROG}: {verb} to PR #{pr_id} — no findings checked? [y/N] "):
            die("declined. Nothing posted; REVIEW.md untouched.")
        if not confirm(f"{PROG}: an unmodified REVIEW.md may simply be unread — "
                       f"confirm you have read it through and PR #{pr_id} is good "
                       "to approve? [y/N] "):
            die("declined. Nothing posted; REVIEW.md untouched.")
    else:
        counts = f"{len(comments)} inline comment(s), {fold_count} finding(s) folded into the body"
        if pending_comments:
            counts += f", {len(pending_comments)} pending comment(s) of yours"
        verb = ("submit your pending review as a REQUEST_CHANGES" if submit
                else "post a REQUEST_CHANGES review")
        if not confirm(f"{PROG}: {verb} to PR #{pr_id} — {counts}? [y/N] "):
            die("declined. Nothing posted; REVIEW.md untouched.")

    # Post. Two shapes: with no pending review, one create-review POST pinned to
    # the reviewed head; with one, add our findings to it and submit it.
    heads = {"reviewed": head, "local": local_head, "pr": live_head}
    if pending is None:
        recovery = ""
        if moved:
            recovery = (f" The review is pinned to the reviewed commit {head[:12]}; if a "
                        "force-push has since dropped it from the PR, GitHub rejects the "
                        f"pin. Re-prepare in that case: pr-review {pr_id}.")
        # Not the gh() helper: the failure message carries the pin caveat above.
        p = run("gh", "api", "--method", "POST",
                f"repos/{nwo}/pulls/{pr_id}/reviews", "--input", "-", stdin=json.dumps(payload))
        if p.returncode != 0:
            die(f"posting the review failed: {p.stderr.strip() or 'gh error'}.{recovery}")
        try:
            response: dict[str, Any] = json.loads(p.stdout)
        except ValueError:
            response = {}
        review_url = response.get("html_url", "")
        if not review_url:
            die("the POST returned no review URL — treating it as a failure."
                f"{recovery} Response:\n{p.stdout}")
        record: dict[str, Any] = {"payload": payload, "response": response, "heads": heads}
    else:
        review_url = post_augment(nwo, pr_id, pending, pending_comments, comments,
                                  body_text, event, head, diff_text)
        record = {"payload": payload, "review_url": review_url,
                  "pending_review_id": pending.get("id"), "heads": heads}

    # Archive AND mark, marker first: posted.md is both the as-posted snapshot and
    # the guard, so writing it first closes the double-post window as early as
    # possible. A failure after a successful post is reported loudly. The heads are
    # recorded post-mortem only — which comments GitHub will have marked outdated;
    # nothing else on disk captures that they had parted.
    rc = mark_posted(review_url, record)
    if rc:
        return rc

    log(f"posted: {review_url}")

    # The review is live and the markers are written — everything went fine, so offer
    # to wipe the local artifacts (.pr-review/, .pr-review-run/, REVIEW.md, and their
    # .git/info/exclude entries). A pause, not a confirmation: posting was the
    # decision, so Enter removes them and Ctrl-C keeps them for a post-mortem. A
    # non-interactive run keeps them too (pause returns False); declining loses nothing.
    if pause(f"{PROG}: press Enter to remove the review artifacts "
             "(.pr-review/, .pr-review-run/, REVIEW.md), or Ctrl-C to keep them "
             "for a post-mortem. "):
        git_dir = Path(git("rev-parse", "--absolute-git-dir",
                           what="locating the git dir"))
        removed = run_cleanup(Path(top), git_dir)
        log(f"removed {', '.join(removed)}. This preparation is closed; "
            f"re-prepare (pr-review {pr_id}) to review the current head afresh.")
    else:
        log("artifacts kept. REVIEW.md stays at the repo root — unchecked "
            "findings survive for a follow-up, and pr-cleanup removes everything "
            f"when you are done. This preparation is finalized; re-prepare "
            f"(pr-review {pr_id}) to start over.")
    return 0


if __name__ == "__main__":
    raise SystemExit(main(sys.argv[1:]))
